    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. So, if I'm understanding you right, it's basically just a way to make sure neither side gets cheated? Like, if the seller tries to take the money before the house is actually mine, the escrow agent stops them? How do they actually \"guard\" the money though, like is it just sitting in a bank account or something?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Exactly, you've got the core concept down—it's a mutual protection mechanism! If the seller tries to pull a fast one, or if the title isn't clean, the escrow agent, who is usually a lawyer or a specialized title company, acts as the gatekeeper. They are much more reliable than a single, greedy individual, which is a big difference from dealing with a rogue third-party. These escrow funds are almost always held in a dedicated, insured trust account at a reputable financial institution. This bank account is specifically designated for the transaction, keeping the money completely separate from the escrow agent's personal funds.",
